      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1762397923120,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Postgres Architecture",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Postgres Architecture",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "qMs7pBIqOqQqEJZz24LRk",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1235.682549423344,
      "y": 3355.760863568285,
      "width": 1702.187255859375,
      "height": 810,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0K",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 574725732,
      "version": 1377,
      "versionNonce": 278089391,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1762397955972,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Application connects to the postmaster process\nThe postmaster checks the application rights and if sucessful start a new postgress process \nand connects it with the client application.\n\nThe instance doesn't write or read requested data directly to or from disk files instead, it buffers\nthem in a shared memory area which is called the shared buffers.\n\npostgress process acts on the shared buffers and wal buffers and manipulates their contents.\nclient requests a commit , the wal writer process writes and fluhes all wal records resulting.\n\nFrom this transaction to the wal file. As the WAL file-in contrast to the data files. is written strictly\nsequentially \n\nPeriodically background writer process checks the shared bufferrs for dirty pages and writes them to the \nappropriate data files.\n\nIn essance the instance contains at least the three processes WAL writer ,background writer and \ncheck pointer and one postgres process per connection In most cases there are more processes running.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Application connects to the postmaster process\nThe postmaster checks the application rights and if sucessful start a new postgress process \nand connects it with the client application.\n\nThe instance doesn't write or read requested data directly to or from disk files instead, it buffers\nthem in a shared memory area which is called the shared buffers.\n\npostgress process acts on the shared buffers and wal buffers and manipulates their contents.\nclient requests a commit , the wal writer process writes and fluhes all wal records resulting.\n\nFrom this transaction to the wal file. As the WAL file-in contrast to the data files. is written strictly\nsequentially \n\nPeriodically background writer process checks the shared bufferrs for dirty pages and writes them to the \nappropriate data files.\n\nIn essance the instance contains at least the three processes WAL writer ,background writer and \ncheck pointer and one postgres process per connection In most cases there are more processes running.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
