    {
      "id": "e1TezdN1_mGl1Z1oyByhX",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -513.1665019159453,
      "y": 5461.228044092846,
      "width": 1668.275390625,
      "height": 810,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e8590c",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b10",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 825023036,
      "version": 306,
      "versionNonce": 308848572,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1762480684109,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "System Catalog\nThe system catalogs are the place where a relational database management system stores schema \nmetadata, such as information about tables and columns, and internal bookkeeping information. \nPostgreSQL's system catalogs are regular tables. You can drop and recreate the tables, add columns,\ninsert and update values, and severely mess up your system that way. Normally, one should not \nchange the system catalogs by hand, there are normally SQL commands to do that. (For example, \nCREATE DATABASE inserts a row into the pg_database catalog — and actually creates the database \non disk.) There are some exceptions for particularly esoteric operations, but many of those have been\n made available as SQL commands over time, and so the need for direct manipulation of the system \ncatalogs is ever decreasing.\n\n                                                                        OR\n\nMetadata of all cluster objects (such as tables, indexes, data types, or functions)is stored in tables that \nbelong to the system catalog. Each database has its ownset of tables (and views) that describe the \nobjects of this database. Several systemcatalog tables are common to the whole cluster; they do not\n belong to any particular database (technically, a dummy database with a zero id is used), but can \nbeaccessed from all of them.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "System Catalog\nThe system catalogs are the place where a relational database management system stores schema \nmetadata, such as information about tables and columns, and internal bookkeeping information. \nPostgreSQL's system catalogs are regular tables. You can drop and recreate the tables, add columns,\ninsert and update values, and severely mess up your system that way. Normally, one should not \nchange the system catalogs by hand, there are normally SQL commands to do that. (For example, \nCREATE DATABASE inserts a row into the pg_database catalog — and actually creates the database \non disk.) There are some exceptions for particularly esoteric operations, but many of those have been\n made available as SQL commands over time, and so the need for direct manipulation of the system \ncatalogs is ever decreasing.\n\n                                                                        OR\n\nMetadata of all cluster objects (such as tables, indexes, data types, or functions)is stored in tables that \nbelong to the system catalog. Each database has its ownset of tables (and views) that describe the \nobjects of this database. Several systemcatalog tables are common to the whole cluster; they do not\n belong to any particular database (technically, a dummy database with a zero id is used), but can \nbeaccessed from all of them.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "71gNgr7dUzS3Te4J-tBZ9",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -508.50132334451655,
      "y": 6286.7470173071315,
      "width": 1607.9393310546875,
      "height": 90,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#f08c00",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b11",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1870626180,
      "version": 326,
      "versionNonce": 597265596,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1762480727193,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Names of all system catalog tables begin with pg_, like in pg_database.Column names start with a \nthree-letter prefix that usually corresponds to the table name,like in datname.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Names of all system catalog tables begin with pg_, like in pg_database.Column names start with a \nthree-letter prefix that usually corresponds to the table name,like in datname.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "oToGnRHuy14ARjQNtj14x",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -505.4209662016598,
      "y": 6408.091883378559,
      "width": 1597.139404296875,
      "height": 45,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#f08c00",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b12",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1105375676,
      "version": 301,
      "versionNonce": 1849732412,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1762480729560,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "In all system catalog tables, the column declared as the primary key is called oid (object identifier);",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "In all system catalog tables, the column declared as the primary key is called oid (object identifier);",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "phDhN_oq-c0ZDu-I9YPoM",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -493.39130529554944,
      "y": 6537.441597385254,
      "width": 146.37594604492188,
      "height": 45,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#2f9e44",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1F",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 732869820,
      "version": 10,
      "versionNonce": 851392956,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1762480887629,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Schemas",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Schemas",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "BkJZKVqUNCJopNQlt1zqi",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -469.28815370165995,
      "y": 6595.220615242397,
      "width": 1559.51953125,
      "height": 675,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1H",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 739654788,
      "version": 34,
      "versionNonce": 611244548,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1762480992298,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Schemas are namespaces that store all objects of a database. Apart from user schemas, Postgre\noffers several predefined ones:\n\npublic is the default schema for user objects unless other settings are specified.\n\npg_catalog is used for system catalog tables.\n\ninformation_schema provides an alternative view for the system catalog as defined\nby the SQL standard.\n\npg_toast is used for objects related to Toast.\n\npg_temp comprises temporary tables. Although different users create temporary\ntables in different schemas called pg_temp_N, everyone refers to their objects\nusing the pg_temp alias.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Schemas are namespaces that store all objects of a database. Apart from user schemas, Postgre\noffers several predefined ones:\n\npublic is the default schema for user objects unless other settings are specified.\n\npg_catalog is used for system catalog tables.\n\ninformation_schema provides an alternative view for the system catalog as defined\nby the SQL standard.\n\npg_toast is used for objects related to Toast.\n\npg_temp comprises temporary tables. Although different users create temporary\ntables in different schemas called pg_temp_N, everyone refers to their objects\nusing the pg_temp alias.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
